Comment:
¬†@abemejia¬† These could be them before their "epiphanies" we see them realize in Spider-Man and Spider-Man 3. They could've been dragged into the MCU during their final battles with their respective Spider-Men.

Doc Ock clearly didn't realize he was up against another version of Peter, which implies that, at that point, he thought he was still fighting HIS Peter, until MCU Peter removed his suit when he was slammed into the pillar.

Goblin, Doc, Electro all clearly died at the end of their respective films. So I think all the villains were dragged into the MCU, either before their final battle with Spider-Man, or right before their deaths.

Which if they were dragged right before their deaths, that would also put Toby and Andrew within the vicinity of being dragged in as well.

I am beginning to believe that Toby and Andrew are in it, but edited out of the trailer, for obvious reasons. I'm still not gonna hype myself up to the point that I'll state it as a fact though. I'm not going into this movie with those expectations just to be disappointed. Because if it turns out they're not in it, a lot of people will be disappointed and will blame the movie, when the real blame lies with themselves.

So if they're in it, I want them to NOT show them or reference them in ANY future trailer and I hope they will save their appearance strictly for the movie.

But I'm still gonna go into this film as if it won't have Toby and Andrew. Honestly, I think Tom's Spider-Man can handle himself and Spider-Man fighting by himself, pushing his limit against multiple enemies with high stakes is what defines Spider-Man.

Comment: Definitely hyped way too much. It's all nostalgia and no story. Literally he does the most irresponsible things and proves Jamie Jameson right. He ruins Peter's life in every universe (everyone who knows Peter Parker has to forget him in every universe) and he allowed the villains to destroy and terrorize the city including even allowing people to get injured/killed. I mean the level to which we have to suspend reality to pretend that nobody was in that New York apartment building is ridiculous. And the idea that Doctor Strange would just say "good job" is stupid. He should know that all of that stuff has repercussions. Ultimately this Spiderman takes a new spin on the line: "With great power comes great responsibility." He essentially uses that to force his broken morality onto others and Aunt May encourages it. He uses that line to justify wresting authority from the hands of Doctor Strange and other authorities and enforces his own morals at the risk of other people's lives. Seriously this is the stupidest Spiderman ever.
